1
00:00:01,229 --> 00:00:27,911
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhassa

2
00:00:29,512 --> 00:00:33,557
Homage to the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened One.

3
00:00:42,649 --> 00:00:50,201
The Buddha's teaching on anatta, not self, is a hard aspect of the Dhamma to understand.

4
00:00:51,563 --> 00:00:54,826
We will all be grappling with it till the moment of enlightenment.

5
00:00:55,987 --> 00:01:07,418
To motivate ourselves for the challenge, it's worth reflecting on the suffering we experience because of identifying with our body, our mind, our life stories.

6
00:01:09,439 --> 00:01:12,102
Take the example of role identification.

7
00:01:13,183 --> 00:01:22,852
Whatever role we're playing in life, father, daughter, gardener, we want to do it well, which is a good motive, no problem there.

8
00:01:23,772 --> 00:01:25,353
It's when we over-identify,

9
00:01:25,739 --> 00:01:29,945
can't see beyond our role that dukkha suffering emerges.

10
00:01:31,549 --> 00:01:38,340
On a good day, we get a buzz out of doing things well, cooking a meal, mending a puncture, teaching a class.

11
00:01:39,462 --> 00:01:41,484
But we all have days when these go wrong.

12
00:01:42,746 --> 00:01:46,132
The sponge cake turns out as a stodgy lump.

13
00:01:46,153 --> 00:01:48,956
The tyre deflates the minute we put the wheel back on.

14
00:01:49,819 --> 00:01:51,882
We go blank when trying to teach.

15
00:01:53,397 --> 00:01:56,140
This is when the Duke of Identification is felt.

16
00:01:57,141 --> 00:02:04,990
The more we identify as a good cook, a good DIYer, a good teacher, the harder it is to bear the letdown.

17
00:02:06,091 --> 00:02:07,733
We can't stop thinking about it.

18
00:02:07,974 --> 00:02:08,716
What went wrong?

19
00:02:09,537 --> 00:02:11,438
How could I have made such a mess of things?

20
00:02:12,319 --> 00:02:13,320
What did they think of me?

21
00:02:14,323 --> 00:02:15,644
We look for someone to blame.

22
00:02:16,344 --> 00:02:18,848
If he hadn't interrupted, it would have been perfect.

23
00:02:20,717 --> 00:02:34,031
While none of us enjoy those times when we've made a hash of something, it is worth dwelling on them long enough to acknowledge that the source of the misery is not actually the gooey mess or the deflating tire.

24
00:02:34,871 --> 00:02:38,895
It's the sense of me and how badly I've let myself down.

25
00:02:38,914 --> 00:02:49,104
That's the real nope, a loss of confidence, perhaps an almost desperate need to reassert ourselves, prove our ability.

26
00:02:50,705 --> 00:03:01,438
The more clearly we can acknowledge the suffering that comes from identification, the more we will be willing to explore the difficult Buddhist teaching of an atta, not self.

27
00:03:02,639 --> 00:03:05,584
And there is no doubt an atta is a difficult nut to crack.

28
00:03:07,526 --> 00:03:15,317
We all have a strong sense that we are the ones baking the cake, mending the tire, teaching the class, living our life.

29
00:03:16,679 --> 00:03:20,002
It's hard to even toy with the idea that this might not be so.

30
00:03:22,143 --> 00:03:28,012
The Buddha's advice is to keep breaking down experience into smaller and smaller chunks.

31
00:03:28,032 --> 00:03:30,616
It's easier to get glimpses of the truth in these.

32
00:03:30,675 --> 00:03:37,265
Then gradually over time, the notion of not-self becomes easier to contemplate.

33
00:03:38,788 --> 00:03:47,942
We start to see its benefits, how much easier life is when we're not identified by our roles or opinions or abilities or achievements.

34
00:03:49,264 --> 00:03:51,407
It's wonderful to have nothing to defend.

35
00:03:52,990 --> 00:04:05,346
One instruction from the Satipatthana Sutta, the four foundations of mindfulness, that I found very helpful for exploring anatta is the advice to practice internally and externally.

36
00:04:06,967 --> 00:04:15,138
Internal can be interpreted to mean our subjective felt experience, while external means our mental understanding of it.

37
00:04:16,779 --> 00:04:20,365
We feel the sensations of breathing for internal practice

38
00:04:20,985 --> 00:04:24,110
For external practice, we reflect that we are breathing.

39
00:04:25,572 --> 00:04:31,098
The Mahalasingh noting technique provides a way of practicing both internally and externally.

40
00:04:32,480 --> 00:04:36,846
We feel the breath and at the same time make a mental note of it.

41
00:04:37,747 --> 00:04:40,370
Same for walking, eating, talking.

42
00:04:41,572 --> 00:04:48,781
All of life can be known both internally as moment-to-moment sensations and feelings, and externally.

43
00:04:48,964 --> 00:04:52,307
as our objective mental perception of what's happening.

44
00:04:55,031 --> 00:04:57,274
Say we are practising mindfulness of breathing.

45
00:04:58,173 --> 00:05:02,598
Feeling the sensations of breathing is to practise mindfulness internally.

46
00:05:03,899 --> 00:05:09,446
Although we don't usually make the thought conscious, we assume we are the one who's sitting here breathing.

47
00:05:11,648 --> 00:05:18,194
If we're also practising externally, then we're noting rising, falling as we track the breath.

48
00:05:19,187 --> 00:05:23,312
As concentration deepens, it can seem like our identity shifts.

49
00:05:24,392 --> 00:05:37,185
Instead of being the one who is sitting here breathing, we sense ourselves as the observer, some sort of a spaced-out entity hovering around our head, the one who is watching the body breathing.

50
00:05:38,747 --> 00:05:46,495
On a good day, we'll also be able to watch our thoughts coming and going, watch emotions rise and fade,

51
00:05:47,386 --> 00:05:49,608
realize we don't have to get caught up in them.

52
00:05:52,011 --> 00:05:56,096
All of this is helping us disentangle our confusion about identity.

53
00:05:57,497 --> 00:06:03,483
Internally, we feel ourselves breathing, thinking, growing happy one moment, sad the next.

54
00:06:04,665 --> 00:06:11,952
But because of our external perspective, we realize we don't need to identify with our thoughts, emotions, breathing.

55
00:06:12,934 --> 00:06:15,536
We see this as happening of their own accord.

56
00:06:15,836 --> 00:06:21,345
driven by various stimuli, but not driven by what I now think of as me.

57
00:06:24,088 --> 00:06:38,970
This can be a lovely experience, a sense of coming home, having found our true self, a sort of disembodied entity that hovers in and around the body, equanimous, interested, watching the show without getting caught up in it.

58
00:06:40,992 --> 00:06:43,476
But after a while, we might grow uncomfortable.

59
00:06:44,317 --> 00:06:45,759
Things start to feel sticky.

60
00:06:46,228 --> 00:06:51,615
as if there's a sheet of velcro passing over each sensation, pulling us along with it.

61
00:06:53,678 --> 00:06:59,867
We start getting caught up with experience again, identified with thoughts and feelings and emotions.

62
00:07:01,310 --> 00:07:11,764
We are again the one who is sitting here breathing and now anxiously trying to find our way back to the lofty crow's nest from which we've been able to observe the show.

63
00:07:13,870 --> 00:07:22,437
Although there's a temptation to see this as bad meditation, we should really see it as a precious opportunity to learn the Dhamma more deeply.

64
00:07:23,759 --> 00:07:28,483
Payment Children likens these episodes as rocket fuel for enlightenment.

65
00:07:31,146 --> 00:07:41,776
To take a practical example, we got a new connector for our gas canister the other day, and so I overcame all my fears about gas and explosions.

66
00:07:42,757 --> 00:07:43,759
I went to hook it up.

67
00:07:44,752 --> 00:07:49,579
After about a dozen failed attempts, all the bits eventually came together.

68
00:07:49,999 --> 00:07:50,920
It looked perfect.

69
00:07:52,362 --> 00:07:55,266
But gas started leaking the moment I opened the cylinder.

70
00:07:56,528 --> 00:08:00,293
I took it apart, reread the instructions, reconnected it.

71
00:08:00,915 --> 00:08:01,615
Still no go.

72
00:08:02,076 --> 00:08:02,916
Disappointing.

73
00:08:04,439 --> 00:08:07,242
I was then asked to look at the printer because it wasn't working.

74
00:08:08,345 --> 00:08:10,146
It needed a new toner cartridge.

75
00:08:11,209 --> 00:08:13,391
And again, I overcame my deep suspicion.

76
00:08:13,810 --> 00:08:18,476
of all things electrical and mechanical, and managed to replace the cartridge.

77
00:08:19,458 --> 00:08:20,098
But no go.

78
00:08:23,884 --> 00:08:27,629
Every page came out white as snow with nothing at all being printed.

79
00:08:29,331 --> 00:08:36,602
Again, I took it all apart, reread the instructions, watched a few videos on replacing the cartridge, tried again.

80
00:08:37,283 --> 00:08:38,085
Still no go.

81
00:08:38,686 --> 00:08:39,847
Another disappointment.

82
00:08:41,509 --> 00:08:43,513
And this time I felt the edge of bad humour.

83
00:08:44,287 --> 00:08:50,114
My mind was starting to close up, feel oppressed by others and by the world in general.

84
00:08:51,995 --> 00:08:58,844
A bit later, Banty came over, took the cartridge out and in his own words, gave it a few thumbs and put it back in place.

85
00:08:59,785 --> 00:09:03,570
Lo and behold, it worked perfectly.

86
00:09:03,590 --> 00:09:12,740
Of course, I was impressed and amused and grateful, but alongside these happy responses, my incipient bad humour gave a painful kick within.

87
00:09:13,750 --> 00:09:15,371
Why couldn't it have worked for me?

88
00:09:15,392 --> 00:09:21,158
I decided to go to my room to explore this more deeply.

89
00:09:22,341 --> 00:09:26,985
Rationally, it was just silliness, the mind building a mountain out of a molehill.

90
00:09:28,107 --> 00:09:38,220
And yet there was not quite a mountain, but certainly more than a molehill of frustration at my failure to connect up a gas cylinder and change a toner cartridge.

91
00:09:39,662 --> 00:09:43,706
But what was more distressing was the admission of being so emotionally impacted

92
00:09:44,158 --> 00:09:45,561
by such trivial matters.

93
00:09:47,283 --> 00:09:53,513
What was the point of decades of Dhamma practice only to be getting distraught over nothing?

94
00:09:53,533 --> 00:09:56,677
This is the dukkha, the suffering of identification.

95
00:09:58,059 --> 00:10:03,128
Identifying with self as manager, the one who is supposed to sort out problems.

96
00:10:04,931 --> 00:10:10,960
Identification with self as meditator, who should by now have developed outstanding equanimity.

97
00:10:12,390 --> 00:10:21,342
Not to speak of self as meditation teacher who should know the Dharma upside down and be able to instantly see through this latest delusion.

98
00:10:23,745 --> 00:10:26,889
As always, mindfulness allowed the storm to blow itself out.

99
00:10:27,890 --> 00:10:40,187
Looking back now, I sense the truth of Pema's children's advice to see these times when our buttons are pressed and we feel like a two year old again as a rocket fuel for enlightenment.

100
00:10:42,344 --> 00:10:51,034
Emotional storms have so much energy that negative thoughts and feelings we normally suppress come skyrocketing into consciousness.

101
00:10:52,918 --> 00:11:00,548
In the light of awareness, their pain becomes so acute that our system is forced to learn a new way of coping with the dukkha.

102
00:11:02,309 --> 00:11:11,642
This new coping mechanism, learned from within, from moment to moment awareness, opens up new pathways for energy flow in the body.

103
00:11:12,246 --> 00:11:13,849
and new doorways in the mind.

104
00:11:15,671 --> 00:11:21,836
We discover new thoughts and perspectives which are gentler, kinder, more patient and forgiving.

105
00:11:25,061 --> 00:11:35,351
In my own example, a new doorway opened because of feeling so acutely the pain of identification, how it traps the mind in a prison of delusion.

106
00:11:37,052 --> 00:11:40,397
The pain of this prison sharpened when the storyline

107
00:11:41,018 --> 00:11:49,048
of me who should be better at everything had fallen away, and I could more clearly feel the emotional patterns underlying the thoughts.

108
00:11:50,971 --> 00:12:09,995
Practising mindfulness internally, I could feel how eagerly the body and mind pounced on a pleasant feeling, sending tentacles of energy around it to clutch and hold as mine, while a bright light switched on in my head, which I perceived as me,

109
00:12:10,330 --> 00:12:13,153
confident, on top of things, in control.

110
00:12:14,934 --> 00:12:20,880
A whirlpool of energy raised around my chest and head to sustain this delight.

111
00:12:23,182 --> 00:12:31,412
The feeling of confidence was gorgeous, but watching it, the external perspective showed up the craziness and pain underneath.

112
00:12:32,653 --> 00:12:36,777
Seeing this, I desperately wanted to escape the prison of identification.

113
00:12:38,798 --> 00:12:51,677
The external perspective let me recognise the crazy whirlpool of energy and the bright light as what the Buddha terms upadana, usually translated as grasping or clinging.

114
00:12:51,697 --> 00:12:54,241
It's also sometimes referred to as selfing.

115
00:12:55,803 --> 00:13:04,738
What is happening is that unskilful desire, tanha, has driven us to create a new identity so as to fulfil this desire.

116
00:13:07,063 --> 00:13:16,474
The better we get to know this experience of selfing, the more we are persuaded of the Buddhist teaching on anatta, not self.

117
00:13:16,494 --> 00:13:23,441
Knowing from our direct experience that a me has suddenly arisen makes it hard to take me too seriously.

118
00:13:28,186 --> 00:13:33,932
We start to see how various mes arise and fade depending on external stimuli.

119
00:13:35,649 --> 00:13:39,854
When things go well, a happy, pleased, self-confident me emerges.

120
00:13:41,174 --> 00:13:47,941
But that fades quickly when things go wrong and the deflated, miserable me takes its place instead.

121
00:13:49,923 --> 00:13:53,966
Back to my own example of watching the fallout from my emotional storm.

122
00:13:55,288 --> 00:14:03,294
Internally, I was experiencing the selfing process, which was generating a confident, delighted sense of me.

123
00:14:04,523 --> 00:14:07,966
one who could fix all the printers and gas cylinders in the world.

124
00:14:08,907 --> 00:14:12,029
However, the external perspective knew this as delusion.

125
00:14:13,611 --> 00:14:23,581
Undermined by that news, the confident self suddenly collapsed into a timid, scared, stiff entity which felt it had no rights to exist.

126
00:14:25,303 --> 00:14:32,691
A moment later, the confident self reappeared, wildly insisting it was totally in control of the situation.

127
00:14:34,730 --> 00:14:40,177
This yo-yo between elated confidence and abject fear continued for some time.

128
00:14:41,899 --> 00:14:45,666
Both identities felt excruciatingly painful and vulnerable.

129
00:14:47,227 --> 00:14:58,804
There was a strong desire to abandon the meditation, but I persisted, allowing my emotional roller coaster to take its course, trusting that a lesson would eventually be learned.

130
00:15:00,567 --> 00:15:04,432
In Vipassana, we can't interfere, we can't tell ourselves

131
00:15:04,700 --> 00:15:06,001
to stop being deluded.

132
00:15:07,403 --> 00:15:11,107
We have to bear patiently with our greeds, hatreds and delusions.

133
00:15:12,129 --> 00:15:14,572
Trust them to burn out in the light of awareness.

134
00:15:15,153 --> 00:15:17,576
Teach us the Dhamma as we suffer their flames.

135
00:15:20,840 --> 00:15:25,264
And sure enough, the energy of the roller coaster gradually diminished.

136
00:15:25,284 --> 00:15:33,475
As it did, so my attention extended gingerly beyond the whirlpool of elated and fearful energies in my chest and head.

137
00:15:34,399 --> 00:15:37,283
to sense my arms, legs, my body sitting.

138
00:15:38,703 --> 00:15:41,025
I couldn't really feel these in any detail.

139
00:15:41,947 --> 00:15:44,089
I only knew them as fake suggestions.

140
00:15:46,049 --> 00:15:49,774
They seemed like strangers from another world, alien, scary.

141
00:15:51,014 --> 00:16:00,322
Luckily, curiosity was stronger than fear, and each outbreath let awareness rest more attentively in the seemingly alien body.

142
00:16:02,085 --> 00:16:04,407
At last, some feelings rippled through.

143
00:16:05,062 --> 00:16:12,049
They were unpleasant and carried the message that the heady whirlpool of confidence was not me, not mine.

144
00:16:12,090 --> 00:16:18,216
The emotionally energetic, deluded part of myself felt this as a threat.

145
00:16:19,378 --> 00:16:23,322
But some wisdom emerged from the depths to welcome the unpleasantness.

146
00:16:24,524 --> 00:16:28,908
Here was something I would not want to cling to, therefore very welcome.

147
00:16:31,690 --> 00:16:39,399
Letting attention rest on the unpleasantness became a non-interfering way of containing and restraining the deluded self.

148
00:16:40,961 --> 00:16:50,894
Gradually, the energetic, bright-light me felt glad of being contained and limited, embodied rather than a totally deluded mental entity.

149
00:16:52,898 --> 00:16:54,500
It became like looking in a mirror.

150
00:16:56,042 --> 00:17:01,308
Perhaps we've all had similar experiences where we sense ourselves as both watching

151
00:17:01,558 --> 00:17:02,519
and being watched.

152
00:17:04,103 --> 00:17:10,211
Sometimes I was the watcher, the observer, the disembodied entity that hovers near my head.

153
00:17:11,232 --> 00:17:13,876
This was the external mindful perspective.

154
00:17:15,259 --> 00:17:16,781
Sometimes I was the mirror image.

155
00:17:17,221 --> 00:17:29,220
This was the internal mindfulness perspective, bringing the embodied experience of me, the experience of sitting and breathing and knowing that I was being watched.

156
00:17:31,798 --> 00:17:36,644
The desire to know who I really am has always been very strong for me.

157
00:17:37,605 --> 00:17:45,453
And part of me that was observing, watching, felt this now as an almost overwhelming attraction towards the mirror image.

158
00:17:46,535 --> 00:17:49,739
I wanted to grasp hold of the image, devour it even.

159
00:17:50,960 --> 00:17:56,145
But whenever I gave in to that desire, it was as if I'd gobbled up my own reflection.

160
00:17:57,406 --> 00:18:01,131
All that was left were little shivers of fear and grief

161
00:18:02,106 --> 00:18:05,790
as I realised how I destroyed what I desired.

162
00:18:06,913 --> 00:18:15,021
I had to suffer the fear and grief, wait patiently till peace prevailed, before I could again glimpse the mirror image.

163
00:18:18,045 --> 00:18:21,650
I became grateful for any unpleasant sensations in the mirror image.

164
00:18:22,309 --> 00:18:28,096
These acted like repulsive forces, countering the attempt to grasp and own the image.

165
00:18:29,291 --> 00:18:32,095
They carried the message, this isn't who you really are.

166
00:18:32,134 --> 00:18:41,644
That understanding also helped me not to grasp and thereby destroy the image of me that I desired so deeply.

167
00:18:42,885 --> 00:18:48,071
I became grateful for the fact that the body can repel the mind as well as attract it.

168
00:18:53,438 --> 00:18:57,662
By this stage, I'd forgotten altogether about my sense of having let myself down.

169
00:18:58,132 --> 00:18:59,433
It just wasn't an issue.

170
00:19:00,355 --> 00:19:06,261
And I was very glad I'd persisted with the meditation, hadn't given up at the height of the emotional storm.

171
00:19:07,784 --> 00:19:16,075
The great gift of sitting with the misery was that the message, this is not who you really are, became for the first time totally welcome.

172
00:19:17,856 --> 00:19:22,462
As the meditation went on, the message brought joy, relief, gratitude.

173
00:19:23,744 --> 00:19:27,108
I understood it as necessary to counter the strong desire

174
00:19:27,663 --> 00:19:35,234
to identify with my body and mind, the only reflection I can find for whatever it is I sense myself to be.

175
00:19:38,179 --> 00:19:45,210
In subsequent meditations and in daily life, I was better able to recognise all mes as temporary and conditional.

176
00:19:46,652 --> 00:19:51,720
I could smile at them, appreciate them, but not be surprised when they dissolved.

177
00:19:52,760 --> 00:19:53,923
This is such a gift.

178
00:19:55,185 --> 00:20:01,252
The deluded me expects too much of me, expects me always to be on top of everything.

179
00:20:02,634 --> 00:20:13,886
Being able to see myself as limited brings forth compassion, as well as appreciation for whatever efforts I make to follow the path, fulfill my various roles.

180
00:20:15,587 --> 00:20:23,336
And if I'm getting a bit heated in conversation, clinging to my opinion, then I can focus on some unpleasant sensation

181
00:20:23,958 --> 00:20:31,263
and welcomed them as messengers, that this strongly opinionated one is not your true self either.

182
00:20:33,346 --> 00:20:41,913
Again, this brings a smile and allows me to be more flexible, ready to change my mind and see the other's point of view.

183
00:20:41,953 --> 00:20:52,462
I hope this illustration of working with the dukkha of identification encourages you to explore the teaching around anatta, not self.

184
00:20:53,624 --> 00:21:01,832
and perhaps also see how those external and internal mindfulness perspectives can help with this challenging teaching.

185
00:21:03,534 --> 00:21:16,405
In this way, may we all see through our identification as daughter, manager, cook or whatever, see these as temporary, conditional, not ever designed to be satisfactory.

186
00:21:17,788 --> 00:21:22,332
As the Buddha said, whatever is inconstant, conditioned,

187
00:21:22,784 --> 00:21:26,790
unsatisfactory, is not worthy of being thought of as me.

188
00:21:28,494 --> 00:21:32,342
We sell ourselves short by investing in these limited identities.

189
00:21:33,584 --> 00:21:40,096
Our continued practice leads us to a truth, a resting place beyond all such limitations.

190
00:21:41,519 --> 00:21:45,365
May we all experience the peace and bliss of Nibbana.

